{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508485"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2761"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2761"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.26,0.13,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2761"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84421"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3016"},{"type":"tags","id":"3101"},{"type":"tags","id":"3322"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4457"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9334"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32 weeks pregnant woman attends her antenatal appointment. Her pregnancy is going smoothly, but she describes feeling fatigued, sleeping a lot and needing to eat more. Her mood has been up and down during the last few months. She completed the Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale (EPDS) at her GP appointment two weeks ago and scored 7. She denies any thoughts of self harm or suicidal ideation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring her appointment the midwife asks her to fill out another EPDS. She scores a total of 8.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is true about the EPDS tool in this context?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is used to diagnose mental health conditions","It cannot be used to screen for perinatal anxiety","Her scores of 7 and 8 indicates persisting significant distress","EPDS should not be used in the antenatal period","A score of 13 or more requires further assessment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe EPDS is a screening tool used in the perinatal period for identifying women who may have anxiety and/or depression and may benefit from follow-up care. Despite its name, it is used in both the antenatal and postnatal setting. It should first be completed early in the in the pregnancy (first trimester), again later in the pregnancy (second-third trimester), 6-12 weeks postpartum and again within the first year after birth. Evidence shows that early identification and management of perinatal depression or anxiety results in better outcomes for mothers, families, and babies. It is used to screen for perinatal depression and anxiety. The scale can be used to screen for perinatal anxiety in particular. It is used as a screening questionnaire to identify woman who may be at risk or suffering from mental health conditions in the perinatal period. It is NOT used for diagnosis. Further assessment is required to diagnose conditions such as depression or anxiety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe scale comprises of 10 questions that ask about how the mother has been feeling over the previous seven days. A score of 0 is the lowest and a score of 30 is the highest. The higher the score, the more symptoms of anxiety or depression the woman has experienced in the last week. \u003Cstrong\u003EA score of 13 or more requires further assessment\u003C/strong\u003E such as referral to a specialist perinatal mental health service. A score of 10-12 requires further discussion regarding certain questions they score high on and a repeat EPDS should be done soon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of 8 is low and does not require further assessment. A score of 0-9 may indicate that some symptoms of distress are present; however, they may be less likely to interfere with daily function. Regardless of score, if these symptoms have persisted for more 1-2 weeks, further investigation should be considered. Question 10 of the EPDS is of particular importance as it assesses thoughts of self-harm or suicide. If the patient scores anything other than 0 for this question further assessment is required and a risk assessment should be done. If they answer \u2018sometimes\u2019 = 2 or \u2018yes, quite often\u2019 = 3 there is significant risk and further assessment may be required urgently.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale should be used at least twice during pregnancy and twice after birth to screen for perinatal depression or anxiety","The Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale has a cut off of 13 or more that suggests the woman requires further assessment","Scores of 0-9 may require further enquiry if symptoms persist for longer than 1-2 weeks or the patient has thoughts of self harm or suicide"],"references":["COPE: Centre of Perinatal Excellence. Perinatal depression Health Professional. Australian Clinical Practice Guideline. 2017. Access at: https://www.cope.org.au/health-professionals/health-professionals-3/perinatal-mental-health-disorders/perinatal-depression/.","Black Dog Institute. The Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale (EPDS). Black Dog Institute. 2020. Access at: https://www.blackdoginstitute.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/edinburgh-postnatal-depression-scale.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84421"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2761"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84421"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T18:40:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T18:40:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2761"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101963"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description